there. When they finish their assignment, they download the project from RStudio Cloud,

00:26:51.119 --> 00:26:59.599
and they upload it into the learning management system on their assignment, so we can

00:26:59.599 --> 00:27:05.280
keep track of the submissions and everything. And we can always, in RStudio Cloud, we can

00:27:05.280 --> 00:27:11.599
always go and pick in their projects and see what they have been doing in the cloud once they have

00:27:11.599 --> 00:27:18.479
submitted the assignment. We also use RStudio Cloud for the group work that we have in the

00:27:18.479 --> 00:27:27.280
unit, and also I run a semester assessment with all the students. So the assignments, I launch

00:27:27.280 --> 00:27:35.040
them via the learning management system. In our case, we use Moodle, and it's something I create

00:27:35.040 --> 00:27:39.439
an assignment for those of you who are familiar with Moodle, but any of the other learning

00:27:39.439 --> 00:27:45.359
management system works the same way. I create the assignment, and then there is a link that takes

00:27:45.359 --> 00:27:52.719
them to the assignment RStudio Cloud space, and then the students, they click on the assignment

00:27:52.719 --> 00:27:59.760
and they start working on the project. So you can see there, for example, 265 projects were derived

00:27:59.760 --> 00:28:06.959
from assignment one. They work in the assignment, they download the project, and then they submit it

00:28:07.920 --> 00:28:14.160
into the learning management system. Also, the reason why I ask them to download the project

00:28:14.160 --> 00:28:20.319
and submit it is I want to also kind of make sure the project hasn't changed after the submission

00:28:20.319 --> 00:28:29.199
date in RStudio Cloud. So the other piece of assessment that I do using RStudio Cloud,

00:28:29.199 --> 00:28:35.520
which the first year was a little bit like, it has worked very well the two years I made it, but

00:28:35.520 --> 00:28:42.640
the first year, it was a bit nerve-wracking to have almost 300 students doing this assessment

00:28:42.640 --> 00:28:49.839
at the same time, and everything had to run smoothly. And as I said, the first year was a

00:28:49.839 --> 00:28:55.680
little bit more nerve-wracking. The second year, it ran really smoothly. So this semester assessment

00:28:55.680 --> 00:29:03.439
is a time exercise that runs over two hours. So it's kind of like an exam, if you wish.

00:29:04.800 --> 00:29:13.199
I launched it via the learning management system. So for this piece of assessment, I create

00:29:13.199 --> 00:29:20.880
a different RStudio Cloud space in which I invite the students before to make sure everyone has

00:29:20.880 --> 00:29:29.119
access. Once they access, it is time, and it's the same time for all the students.

00:29:29.680 --> 00:29:34.719
They start working on the assignment in RStudio Cloud, and then once they complete the

00:29:34.719 --> 00:29:41.760
assignment, they download the project with all the files, and they submit it again via the

00:29:41.760 --> 00:29:50.319
learning management system. So in order to deal with any possible technical issues, we have a

00:29:50.800 --> 00:29:58.079
Zoom call open for technical support. So the Zoom call is not open for the students

00:29:58.079 --> 00:30:04.560
to try to get help about the exercise. No, it's just for technical support. So if someone...

00:30:06.160 --> 00:30:12.959
Usually, there are not many issues, but sometimes some students, they keep

00:30:12.959 --> 00:30:19.199
being kicked out of their project, and sometimes I have to kind of download, delete them, and create

00:30:19.199 --> 00:30:25.439
like give them access again, but that's really a minority. As I said, it runs very smoothly,

00:30:25.439 --> 00:30:32.479
but having this Zoom call open, it gives the students the peace of mind that if something

00:30:32.479 --> 00:30:39.680
happened, they can always contact us. So just to wrap it up, some thoughts.

00:30:39.839 --> 00:30:44.640
RStudio Cloud really, I think, is great for...

00:30:47.119 --> 00:30:55.040
To kind of lead students in their first R journey. It removes the installation

00:30:55.040 --> 00:31:01.920
burdens. It actually kind of avoids the problem of dealing with different operating

00:31:01.920 --> 00:31:07.599
systems or computers with different specs. It definitely facilitates the remote and online

00:31:07.599 --> 00:31:14.640
learning because I can always see other students cloning the project. Are they

00:31:14.640 --> 00:31:20.880
working? And if some students have some issue, I can always speak in their project, which is really good.

00:31:23.680 --> 00:31:32.880
Also, it gives you kind of like a flexibility to decide how the users access the different

00:31:32.880 --> 00:31:40.640
projects in terms of how much RAM do you need or CPUs. So if you are working with real-life

00:31:40.640 --> 00:31:47.599
examples, you can always make sure things work before you kind of open the exercise to the

00:31:47.599 --> 00:31:55.359
students, and if you need, you can adjust those parameters. I think one thing that is very

00:31:55.359 --> 00:32:02.079
important is to actually keep the connection. For people like us who are more used to use RStudio,

00:32:02.079 --> 00:32:07.599
it's kind of, it seems obvious, right? There is a connection between RStudio Cloud and RStudio.

00:32:07.599 --> 00:32:16.400
When the students, they are first starting their journey into learning R, if we only focus on RStudio

00:32:16.400 --> 00:32:23.040
Cloud, what I have experienced is some of them have trouble understanding what is an R project

00:32:23.040 --> 00:32:29.280
because when I give them a link, they already access, they are already in the project.

00:32:29.280 --> 00:32:34.319
So sometimes at the beginning when they are learning, it's a little bit confusing. That's why

00:32:34.319 --> 00:32:43.920
I try to use RStudio in my desktop for the lectures and RStudio Cloud for the practical

00:32:43.920 --> 00:32:49.920
exercises so the students see how the two things are almost the same but slightly different in the

00:32:49.920 --> 00:32:56.000
way you access to it, mainly because I don't want them to be confused with what is an R project.

00:32:56.880 --> 00:33:04.160
I think it's a very empowering tool, especially, you know, like in the other unit, the reproducible

00:33:04.160 --> 00:33:10.719
and collaborative practices. I want them to build confidence to install the software in

00:33:10.719 --> 00:33:16.800
their local machine and to also use the command line interface and also interact with it through

00:33:16.800 --> 00:33:24.719
the RStudio interface. So I find that it's really empowering and some of them, they really love

00:33:24.800 --> 00:33:31.199
the possibility to go back to RStudio Cloud and try different things with different R versions

00:33:31.199 --> 00:33:34.800
without having to install all of them in their computer. So it's quite good.

